<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> But perhaps, just perhaps, we should consider solutions other than blowing up some random civilians.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The war in Afghanistan is the only war I can think of in which success was determined in how small the body count was. In war, civilians always die. The problem with fighting terrorism is that all the combatants on one side are always civilians. I think we would do well to note that one side of the war on terror intentionally limits civilian casualties, while the other side intentionally targets civilians. In the case of Iraq, the state has frequently and intentionally target civilians. We aren't talking about command and control either.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Sure, we could beat up Iraq. And North Korea<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The US currently has in excess of 30,000 troops in South Korea (not to mention our Pacific fleet in Japan) for the sole purpose of containing North Korea. North Korea has a military numbering approximately one million people, making it the third largest standing army in the world (We might note here that a country with the third largest standing army in the world and a billion-dollar nuclear weapons program has a famine problem so severe that, according to international aid agencies, the orphan problem in North Korea has diminished from cannibalism). The United States would be hard pressed to &quot;beat up&quot; North Korea, as indeed the United Nations discovered in the 1950's. Anyone who has ever been to the DMZ between the North and the South could never be so flip about a potential conflict.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The SDI defense program, which George W Bush wants to resurect (sic)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The Strategic Defense Initiative was resurrected early in the Clinton administration. The administration received a great deal of criticism for this, since the Democrats had a plank against SDI, so it was chopped up into a variety of programs with different names, none of which is SDI. In order to resurrect something, it has to be dead first.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Before that we were developing weapons to win the Vietnam war. Everytime we go to war we develop great weapons to win the war we already fought, weapons which are soon made obsolete.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The United States spends more on military R&amp;D than any European country spends on its military as a whole, in order ensure that the above is false. Ever hear anyone talking about the &quot;Rumsfeld Transformation,&quot; which began before the war on terror began? The transformation was/is to meet the new threats before us.<br>
<br>
Aside from all the above, I assume I will not be able to persuade true believers that the arguments of moral equivalency and isolationism are without merit. I suppose it is a sign of getting old, but I think Jarkell is right about one thing when he writes:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Terrorism is the new Communism.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The same old arguments of moral equivalency and isolationism that used to be used by defenders of communism seem to have been recycled again. When I think back to my days living in the former Soviet Union when privileged westerners would come and delight in the Workers' Paradise (oh, you have only one kind of milk! What a wonderfully simplified life you live here!), I used to think it was kind of funny. I must be getting old; I'm not laughing anymore.<br>
<br>
In the above, I'm afraid I have picked on Jarkell a bit, and I hope he does not take it as an attack on him, though I am obviously disagreeing with his <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> position</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Jarkell's posts got picked apart because he was courageous enough to attempt posting evidence to support his claims, and therefore left a longer and more detailed post. Bravo, Jarkell! I hope that your interest in international politics continues.<br>
<br>
Yours,<br>
Gnosis Bunglefoot <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showPrevMessage?topicID=1582.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showNextMessage?topicID=1582.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1582.topic&index=0><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/classic/addReply.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.threadControl?topicID=1582.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=1582.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=1582.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub94.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option value="firionaviefrm1">Firiona Vie General Chat<option value="firionaviefrm9">OT/OOC Forum<option value="firionaviefrm4">The Soapbox<option value="firionaviefrm58">Telegrams!<option value="firionaviefrm47">Guilds and Associations<option value="firionaviefrm10">A Bard for a Day<option value="firionaviefrm23">Hero Heart Tavern<option value="firionaviefrm15">The Polling Booth<option value="firionaviefrm40">Kudos!<option value="firionaviefrm48">Ye Olde Coffeeshop<option value="firionaviefrm5